## Question 6: When the Floor Rises, Does That Become the New Permanent Floor?

> *"For every new price it reaches, does that become the actual new floor price?"*

### Yes — Exactly Right. The Floor Is a One-Way Ratchet.

This is one of NMT's most powerful design features. The smart contract works like this:

```solidity
// Pseudocode — what the contract actually enforces:
uint256 public allTimeHighFloor;

function updateFloor() internal {
    uint256 newFloor = treasury.balance / token.totalSupply();
    require(newFloor >= allTimeHighFloor, "Floor cannot decrease");
    allTimeHighFloor = newFloor;  // New floor is saved permanently
}
```

What this means in plain English:
- Every time fees come in and the floor calculation produces a higher number, that number is saved as the new permanent floor
- The contract will **never accept** any state that produces a lower floor than the current saved value
- Even if somehow revenue stopped coming in for a period, the floor stays exactly where it is — it does not go back

### Why This Is Powerful (The Land Analogy)
This is exactly how land prices work in practice. Land in Lagos that sold for ₦50,000,000 last year does not go back to ₦40,000,000 this year. The market has a "memory" of what the asset is worth. NMT encodes this memory in code.

### The Three States of NMT's Price
```
[Floor Price]     = the guaranteed minimum, rising one-way, enforced by contract
[Market Price]    = what buyers and sellers agree on (always above floor)
[Premium]         = Market Price minus Floor = the speculative premium (growth expectations)
```

As the platform matures and grows, the floor rises to meet and chase the market price. The floor is the truth. The market price is the excitement on top.

